1. well yes and no. `@option --action` makes absolutely 100% sense in a way. what dont make sense is strict types for AI agents IO. no matter how much i'd live it - your input and output as a LLM is literally tokens/string -> tokens/string and that is true for the MCP protocol as well.   

what i wanted to show was this:

```
./utils/build-declarations.sh scripts/searxng.sh
[
  {
    "name": "main",
    "description": "SearXNG container management",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "action": {
          "type": "string",
          "description": "Action to perform",
          "enum": [
            "up",
            "down",
            "logs",
            "shell"
          ]
        },
        "follow": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "description": "Follow log output (logs only)"
        }
      },
      "required": []
    }
  }
]
```
